    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Species of tall oak native to eastern North America in Canada and the U.S., found in a variety of habitats, including stream valleys and low-lying fields, thus giving it the common name. It has bark that is gray and scaly with irregular ridges and fissures and a bowl-shaped cap of leaves. It grows rapidly and can live to 350 years of age.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
